serving_suggestions.description: ht_ulht_bTortiglioni with broccoli:d_ht_bht_li500 g Tortiglioni d_ht_liht_li1 large bunch of broccoli d_ht_liht_li2 cloves of garlic d_ht_liht_li3/4 cup of De Cecco extra virgin olive oil d_ht_liht_li1/2 tpsn. of hot pepper flakes d_ht_liht_li1/2 cup of grated Parmesan cheese d_ht_liht_lisalt and freshly ground black pepper to taste d_ht_liht_liClean broccoli. Discard the tough part of the stems and remove the springs. Soak stems and springs separately in two bowls of water for 20 minutes. Bring a large pot of salted water to a boil, add the broccoli stems. After two minutes, add the De Cecco Tortiglioni and the broccoli springs. Cook for 12 minutes. Put the De Cecco extra virgin olive oil in a small skillet over a medium heat, add the minced garlic and saute until golden. Season with salt, pepper and hot pepper flakes. Drain pasta and broccoli, add the sauce, sprinkle with Parmesan cheese, toss well and serve immediately. d_ht_lid_ht_ul

serving_suggestions.description: ht_ulht_bSimple homemade pizza:d_ht_bht_emIngredients: d_ht_emht_li2 ½ cups Farina flour d_ht_liht_li1 teaspoon salt d_ht_liht_li1 teaspoon sugar d_ht_liht_li1 tablespoon fast rise yeast d_ht_liht_li1 cup water (120F) d_ht_liht_li1 tablespoon oil d_ht_liht_emTopping: d_ht_emht_li1/4 cup tomato sauce d_ht_liht_li1 teaspoon Italian seasoningd_ht_liht_li1/2 teaspoon garlic powderd_ht_liht_li1/2 teaspoon salt d_ht_liht_li1/8 teaspoon pepper d_ht_liht_li1 ½ cups pepperoni slices d_ht_liht_li1 cup shredded mozzarella cheese d_ht_liht_li1 cup shredded Monterey jack cheese d_ht_liht_li3 tablespoons grated parmesan cheese d_ht_liht_emDirections: d_ht_emht_liIn a bowl mix water and oil; ht_emadd to Farinad_ht_em flour mixture. d_ht_liht_liTurn onto floured surface; knead for 2 minutes. d_ht_liht_liPlace in a greased bowl; turning to grease top. d_ht_liht_liCover and let rise for 20 minutes. d_ht_liht_liPunch down; place on 12in, greased pizza pan. d_ht_liht_liPat into a circle. d_ht_liht_liTopping: Mix first 5 ingredients and spread over crust. d_ht_liht_liPut a few pepperoni slices on top of sauce. d_ht_liht_liSprinkle with 1/2 the mozzarella; 1/2 the Monterey jack, and 1/2 the parmesan. d_ht_liht_liPut the rest of the pepperoni on. d_ht_liht_liRepeat the cheese layer. d_ht_liht_liBake at 400* for 20 minutes or until light brown. d_ht_lid_ht_ul

serving_suggestions.description: ht_bPizza on a stickd_ht_bDirections:ht_ulht_liPreheat oven to 400°. In a large nonstick skillet, cook sausage over medium heat until no longer pink; drain. When cool enough to handle, cut sausage into 20 pieces. On 10 metal or wooden skewers, alternately thread sausage, vegetables and pepperoni d_ht_liht_liUnroll pizza dough onto a lightly floured surface; cut widthwise into 1-in.-wide strips. preview.description: ht_ulht_liWe are proud to bring you a product made with Blue Corn and some of the finest Non-Hydrogenated Oils in the market.d_ht_liht_liThese chips are very thin and crispy with the delicious flavour that blue corn brings to your plate. That is the reason the Aztec Indians prayed and glorified goddess of the corn “Chicomecoatl” to thank her for providing such a delectable crop. Corn was so important to the Aztecs that she was also known as “the goddess of nourishment” and they depicted her carrying the Sun as a shield. Delicious! – The preparation f Nixtamal was a daily task for the housewife, and even now in old Mexico it still occupies upto six hours of woman’s day.d_ht_liht_liThe kernels were steeped in lime overnight to loosen the hull, then boiled and skinned, and finally ground to dough by crushing the kernels between a grooved stone roller and a Metate (Lava rock stone slab). The Nixatamal was usually made into tortillas. d_ht_liht_liTaste the blue corn chips and you will be transported to the Aztecs world and you too will pray to “Chicomecoatl” for more.d_ht_lid_ht_ul
